column49: I do not like this new method of ordering. I would rather pick my order due date than have it assigned by Scholastic. Also, I liked the old way of ordering where students could bring their paper order forms to school for me to enter in if they wanted. Forcing every family to order online does not work for all of my students, especially if they don't have a credit card or have adequate online access for ordering. I have been a Scholastic member for over 30 years, but I do not plan on using it on a regular basis any more. I only used it this time because I had a student whose parent, on her own, searched the site and submitted an order to me. I did not pass out any catalogues or tell students about ordering. Bring back the good literature instead of just the books based on movies or video games. Bring back the $1 books.

column49: Not crazy about this new format that I cannot choose my own due dates and shipping dates for my classroom.  In the past, I handed out orders, gave parents one week to order and placed my order WITH parent orders.  I could count on when books would arrive for families.  I also sent them EVERY month - orders are now much fewer and closer together (November and Holiday) are very close together.  I don't mind parents ordering on-line (that works easier for me), but I don't like the lack of flexibility for my families.

column49: I wanted to read how parents are to order.  I was told by a colleague that if parents send in the order to me they have to figure out tax.  I also am wondering why I am only getting one flyer a month and why it comes so late.  It seems you want parents to order online, but you make it hard for families to look at selections.  We want to hold the books we read, but we cannot hold the flyer to see what is new or offered.  I get going paperless, but I think this will hurt your company.  Thank you for reading and I hope you will adjust and make this more user-friendly for families and teachers.

column49: Scholastic always has been a great source of books that are of decent quality at good prices.  I love getting books into students' hands.  Scholastic makes it easy.   But you know, I have to pause when I think about the recent hubbub of the Book Fairs.  Please don't limit my students' access to diverse books.  Even though there are book bans in states....and how it hasn't reached WV yet, I don't know.   I have to depend on you to give my students those books.  Join teachers and use your voice to help fight book bans, don't just limit the offerings of your books.  I have to keep ordering from you because I'm in rural WV.

column49: I would really like to see the Apple Macbook return to the bonus point catalog.  I've been saving my points for multiple years (even making my book purchases out of pocket to further build my point bank) so that I could have a Macbook in my classroom.  My main purpose for wanting one is so that I can create interactive activities for my students to use on the smartboard and their ipads.  Kindergarten needs so many changes in their daily activities to keep them engaged and this was a solution I planned to use across my curriculum.  I finally was going to have enough points this year.    So please consider bringing it back for us!   ~ a very long time loyal Scholastic customer  Carrie Underhill (cunderhill@wallacegs.org)

column49: The site is fine but the changes to the program are frustrating.  We went from having several flyers to choose from to just one with 1/3 the content.  The books have gotten expensive and are no longer affordable for most of my families.  My  families did much better when the prices didn't have cents...the whole dollar pricing was much easier.  It is hard to find a way to spend my $10 bonus when the books that qualify are books I already have.  The bonuses for having more orders aren't as good as they used to b e either.  I'm disappointed.  This might be my last year as it is hard to earn free books now.

column49: I have been an elementary school teacher for 30+  years.  I've acquired a very large collection of children's books in that time and the majority were bought through Scholastic.  (I even bought from Troll back then).  All these years I have worked with Second Language Learners in Title I schools.  I always gave my students books for birthdays, prizes, Christmas and at the end of the school year.  I encouraged parents to buy books for their children because I knew that Scholastic had the best prices and selection.  Your incentives and rewards for buying from you were the only way I could afford to provide books for my students and classroom.    I always enjoyed giving my book orders to the wonderful customer service representatives and looked forward to receiving my Scholastic box of books. column49: I really dislike the new book order flyers. I don't know if I will continue to use  them this year. They are empty of books to choose from. I feel the flyers underestimate the children's ability to think and learn. I liked that the flyers used to be more technical. My students felt grown up looking at them. Now you don't tell the reading level or number of pages  unless you go online and look the books up. Even though there are little games and quizzes, becuase you now have to have a computer to orders, the flyers are more for the parents and less for the kids.  I teach third grade. I would give out the Seasaw, Lucky, and Arrow. It helped me and the students to pick out books that were appropriate for both their reading level and interests. I very much dislike the flyers now being grade level.  Now parents won't get books for kids because Scholastic says it is a "first grade book" even if it is actually a third grade level reading range.

column49: I wanted to change the next due date, but it seems like that is not possible anymore.  It would be nice if teachers could adjust that easily.    I am disappointed the $1 weekly books and book packs (5 copies of the same book for a reasonable price) have been taken away.  Families are struggling right now and many families could only afford the $1 book, but had options weekly if it was not a book their child would like.  I also tried to get books in the homes of my students would order the 5 book packs to give each child a book at Christmas.  It was affordable and a good Christmas gift, but now it's not.  There are other options for affordable books now that those two options are gone.  That is why I might not recommend your company to colleagues.  I help train new teachers.  I have also started steering them to more affordable options.  I have been teaching for 17 years and I used to like this company a lot.

A lot of the parents don't like ordering online, they don't trust putting their info online.  Or, my parents don't have the means to get a credit card to order products online.  I think it needs to go back to the way it was where parents can choose to send in money to the school or to order online.  It would give more kids the opportunity to get books.

column49: I have been an account holder on Scholastic for over 20 years.  In the past, I have asked for the help of the public to donate money to my classroom so that I could order a book for every student in my class 4 times each year.  This year, I did not even ask because the price of the books has gone up so much that I was not able to get enough money donated for the number of students that I have.  This year, the order form is less than impressive to me.  Overall, I have been very dissatisfied with Scholastic Book Clubs.  It is becoming more and more difficult for teachers to provide students with books and now the cost is higher and the paper order form is not sufficient to meet the needs to classrooms and families.  I hope that more people voice their opinions of the new look this year-I, for one, am not pleased with the prices nor the quantity of available books.

column49: I have been using Scholastic for the last 11 years as a classroom teacher, but have been ordering books from the company since I was in elementary school. I love the books and, up until this year, have been a huge advocate for Scholastic! This year, however, I have been really discouraged and unsatisfied with the major cost increase. I no longer have enough fuds to purchase a book for each of my students each month, there are fewer bonus points, and as a result, much fewer parent orders. This is disappointing and, unless it changes for next year, I won't be continuing the campaign for my class. I understand that the cost of everything has gone up, but as a loyal customer for close to 30 years, I just can't understand how it can change so quickly. It breaks my heart to let go of such a big part of my classroom for the last decade, but I can't afford it and neither can my families.
